The Stroke Prediction Dataset from Kaggle contains 11 clinical features for predicting stroke events of a person. This data set contains 11 predictors and one binary response variable. This classification dataset is used to predict whether a patient is likely to get stroke based on the various predictor parameters like gender, age, various diseases, and smoking status. According to WHO, 2019 report, the non-communicable disease Stroke is the 2nd leading causes of death, responsible for approximately 11% of total deaths. So, an analysis of this data set is thought to be of great relevance. contains 10 clinical predictors like age, bmi, work_type, hypertension, etc. to identify the stroke events in patients. The data set contains 10 clinical predictors like age, bmi, work_type, hypertension, etc.to identify the stroke(Dependent Variable) events in patients.

There is a significant correlation between a patients marital status and their age with a 0.71 correlation index and thats the highest correlation. There is also a positive correlation between patients age and the type of their work with a 0.61 correlation index. Also, age shows not high but positive correlation between hypertension and heart disease, bmi and average glucose level, stroke, and negative correlation to smoking_status. The type of residence of a patient is not correlated with any other attribute. There is also a moderate correlation between work_type and ever_married variables. Only age has a highly significant correlation with some of the other variables and thats obvious. Thus, each feature might have its own individual contribution to the prediction of stroke.

Principal Component Analysis: The summary of PCA is given below in figure.5. In this multivariate analysis, the dataset is transformed into a set of values of linearly uncorrelated variables called principal components. The cumulative proportion of variance explained by different PCs can be observed in figure.5 above. Out of 10 principal components, the first 6 PCs are required to explain 78.14% of variance cumulatively. A scree plot and a cumulative proportion of variance graph are shown in figure.6. It is clear that at least 6 PCS are required to explain about 78% of the variance and 7 are required for explaining 86% variance.

Classification Models: The original dataset is divided into train and test sets using a 70% to 30% train-test split and different models are built on the original data. The different models used are Logistic Regression (LR), K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN), Support Vector Machines (SVM), and Random Forest.

The ROC curve and AUC value of the 4 different models are given in Figure. The higher the AUC value indicates the better model performance. The ROC curve indicates that the Random Forest classification has the better classification efficiency in distinguishing between patients susceptible to stroke and no stroke.

# Combine all ROC curves into one plot
plot(test_roc1, col="red", lwd=2)
plot(test_roc2, add=TRUE, col="green", lwd=2, lty=2)
plot(test_roc3, add=TRUE, col="blue", lwd=2)
plot(test_roc4, add=TRUE, col="black", lwd=2, lty=2)
title(main="ROC Curve of 4 models", font.main=4, line=0)

# Range for the plot
plot_range <- range(0, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.5)

# Get the AUC values and round them
auc_values <- c(
  round(test_roc1$auc, digits=3),
  round(test_roc2$auc, digits=3),
  round(test_roc3$auc, digits=3),
  round(test_roc4$auc, digits=3)
)

# Create legend labels with AUC values
model_labels <- c("svm", "knn", "random forest", "lr")
auc_labels <- paste(model_labels, " (AUC:", auc_values, ")", sep="")

# Add legends for models and AUC values
legend(0.4, plot_range[2], auc_labels, cex=0.8,
       col=c("red", "green", "blue", "black"), lty=1:2, title="Models")

Discussion: The primary objective of this project is to find the different predictors given in the data set that can effectively identify the stroke event in patients so that it leads to better preventive care for patients who are susceptible to stroke. Using Logistic regression, we found that the major predictors are age, hypertension, heart_disease, and avg_glucose_level. Variable importance of Logistic Regression and Random Forest also revealed that age, bmi, and avg_glucose_level are the most significant variables for stroke prediction for the given data. Hypertension, smoking_status, and heart_disease are worth considering as important. Also, PCA is implemented to see whether the dimensionality can be reduced using a lower number of principal components but out of 10 variables, 7 are required to explain more than 80% of the variance explained by the original data. Then we balanced the data using the MWMOTE re-sampling technique and constructed models and reached a conclusion that Random Forest is the best model for the re-sampled data that has high Sensitivity and Specificity values which is crucial for stroke prediction. Better models must be developed since stroke is a serious life-threatening condition. Since the original data is highly imbalanced, more accurate data must be collected instead of applying re-sampling techniques. Varieties of other ML algorithms can also be implemented to see which one can perform better than the suggested Random Forest in this project.
